===Etymology===
''Hello'' (first attested in 1826), from {{m|en|holla}}, {{m|en|hollo}} (attested 1588). This variant of {{m|en|hallo}} is often credited to [[w:Thomas Edison|Thomas Edison]] as a coinage for telephone use, but its appearance in print predates the invention of the telephone by several decades.

Ultimately from a variant of Old English {{m|ang|Ä“alÄ}}, such as {{m|ang|hÄ“lÄ}}, which was used colloquially at the time similarly to how ''hey'' and (in some dialects) ''hi'' are used nowadays. Thus, equivalent to a compound of {{m|en|hey}} and {{m|en|lo}}. Used when drawing attention to yourself.

Possibly influenced by {{ncog|osx|halo|halo!}}, imperative of {{m|osx|halÅn|t=to call, fetch}}, used in hailing a ferryman, akin to {{ncog|goh|hala}}, {{m|goh|hola|hola!}}, imperative forms of {{m|goh|halÅn}}, {{m|goh|holÅn|t=to fetch}}. More at {{l|en|hallo}}.

OED and Merriam-Webster also suggested that it is a variant of {{m|en|holla}}, a variant of {{m|en|holloo}}. Further beyond, the origin remains uncertain. OED and Merriam-Webster suggested that it has a connection between {{m|en|hallow|t= to shout, to cry out loud}}, which came from Old French {{m|fro|holloer}}, which, according to ''AltfranzÃ¶sisches WÃ¶rterbuch'', is from {{cog|osx|halÅn}}.

